    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sep 15. 1871</date>
                    <salute>Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for yr letter of the 12<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>, rec<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> yesterday.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> As you seem desirous that I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> become a shareholder in the Artizan’s Dwelling Co., &amp; as the object seems an excellent one, I shall be happy to take ten shares; &amp; I will send a cheque for £100 on receiving the proper documents.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I return the enclosed letters; &amp; wishing success to the Company in its benevolent purpose | I remain dear Sir | yours faithfully | Charles R. Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">J. Royle Martin Esq</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">3.1 J … Esq] <hi rend="italic">in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The Artizans, Labourers, and General Dwellings Company was founded in 1867 with the intention of building affordable housing for the working classes (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_229.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Artizans’ &amp; General Properties Company Ltd [1967]</ref>, pp. 6–7). CD erroneously recorded the purchase of shares worth £100 on 12 September 1871 in his Investment book (Down House MS).</note>
        </div>        
            
